Capsids are rod-shaped or cubic-spherical protein structures. In some virus types, they consist of multimeric units of only one polypeptide, in other cases they are composed of heteromeric complexes. The capsid protein subunits can aggregate into discrete subunits or even into so-called capsomeres, i.e. morphologically distinct structural components. Rod-shaped capsids have a helical symmetry. The two planes of symmetry, i.e. the longitudinal and the transversal axes, differ in length (Fig. 2.2a). By contrast, spherical capsids have an icosahedral structure with a rotational symmetry; an icosahedron consists of 20 equilateral triangles and 12 vertices (Fig. 2.2b). The symmetry axes have the same length: the fivefold symmetry axis is located at the vertices of the icosahedron; the threefold axis passes through the centre of a triangle, the twofold axis passes along the edges. The number of subunits of an icosahedron can be calculated by the formula \documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
